## User Story
As a user, I want a text input field and a send button to submit my research query, so that I can start a research session from the web interface.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] A `ChatInput` component exists at `web/src/components/chat-input.tsx`
- [ ] The component renders a text input and a "Research" button side-by-side
- [ ] The input accepts multi-line text (textarea behavior) and can be submitted with `Ctrl+Enter`
- [ ] The send button is disabled and shows a loading spinner when `isLoading` prop is `true`
- [ ] The input is cleared after a successful submit
- [ ] The component accepts an `onSubmit: (query: string) => void` prop — it does NOT manage API calls itself
- [ ] The component is rendered on the home page (`src/app/page.tsx`) and is visually acceptable at 375px (mobile) and 1280px (desktop) widths
- [ ] No TypeScript errors (`npm run build` is clean)

## Technical Tasks
1. **Create the component file** at `web/src/components/chat-input.tsx`:
   tsx
   "use client"

   import { useState, KeyboardEvent } from "react"
   import { Button } from "@/components/ui/button"
   import { Textarea } from "@/components/ui/textarea"
   import { SendHorizontal, Loader2 } from "lucide-react"

   type ChatInputProps = {
     onSubmit: (query: string) => void
     isLoading?: boolean
   }

   export function ChatInput({ onSubmit, isLoading = false }: ChatInputProps) {
     const [query, setQuery] = useState("")

     function handleSubmit() {
       const trimmed = query.trim()
       if (!trimmed || isLoading) return
       onSubmit(trimmed)
       setQuery("")
     }

     function handleKeyDown(e: KeyboardEvent<HTMLTextAreaElement>) {
       if (e.key === "Enter" && e.ctrlKey) {
         e.preventDefault()
         handleSubmit()
       }
     }

     return (
       <div className="flex gap-2 w-full">
         <Textarea
           value={query}
           onChange={(e) => setQuery(e.target.value)}
           onKeyDown={handleKeyDown}
           placeholder="What do you want to research? (Ctrl+Enter to send)"
           className="min-h-[60px] resize-none"
           disabled={isLoading}
         />
         <Button onClick={handleSubmit} disabled={isLoading || !query.trim()} size="lg">
           {isLoading ? (
             <Loader2 className="h-4 w-4 animate-spin" />
           ) : (
             <SendHorizontal className="h-4 w-4" />
           )}
         </Button>
       </div>
     )
   }

2. **Add lucide-react** (icon library bundled with shadcn/ui but needs to be imported):
   bash
   cd web && npm install lucide-react

3. **Add `Textarea` from shadcn/ui** if not yet added:
   bash
   npx shadcn@latest add textarea

4. **Wire the component into the home page** (`src/app/page.tsx`):
   tsx
   "use client"
   import { ChatInput } from "@/components/chat-input"

   export default function HomePage() {
     function handleSubmit(query: string) {
       console.log("Research query:", query) // placeholder until M5-6
     }
     return (
       <main className="flex min-h-screen flex-col items-center justify-center p-8 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
         <ChatInput onSubmit={handleSubmit} />
       </main>
     )
   }

5. **Test manually:** Start `npm run dev`, open `http://localhost:3000`, type a query, verify Ctrl+Enter submits (logs to console), verify the button icon shows a spinner when you set `isLoading={true}` temporarily.
6. **Run `npm run build`** and fix any TypeScript errors before closing the issue.

## Context
In React, components should be single-responsibility: `ChatInput` handles capturing user input and signaling intent via the `onSubmit` callback — it does not know about the API. This mirrors the Single Responsibility Principle familiar from Java. The `isLoading` prop pattern is idiomatic React for controlling UI state from a parent component. The actual API wiring happens in M5-6.

## References
- [React: Responding to Events](https://react.dev/learn/responding-to-events) — how onClick, onKeyDown, and event handlers work
- [React: useState Hook](https://react.dev/reference/react/useState) — managing component-local state
- [shadcn/ui: Textarea](https://ui.shadcn.com/docs/components/textarea) — component API and usage examples
- [shadcn/ui: Button](https://ui.shadcn.com/docs/components/button) — variants and disabled state
- [lucide-react](https://lucide.dev/guide/packages/lucide-react) — icon library reference

## User Story
As a user, I want to see a scrollable list of human and AI messages displayed as distinct chat bubbles, so that I can follow the conversation history during a research session.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] A `MessageList` component exists at `web/src/components/message-list.tsx`
- [ ] Human messages render right-aligned with a distinct background (e.g., primary color)
- [ ] AI messages render left-aligned with a neutral background
- [ ] The list scrolls automatically to the bottom when a new message is added
- [ ] An empty state is shown when there are no messages (e.g., "Ask anything to start researching")
- [ ] The component accepts a `messages: Message[]` prop where `Message = { id: string; role: "human" | "ai"; content: string }`
- [ ] The component is integrated into the home page alongside `ChatInput`
- [ ] No TypeScript errors (`npm run build` is clean)

## Technical Tasks
1. **Define the `Message` type** in `web/src/lib/types.ts` (create this file as a shared type module):
   ts
   export type Message = {
     id: string
     role: "human" | "ai"
     content: string
   }

2. **Create `web/src/components/message-list.tsx`:**
   tsx
   "use client"

   import { useEffect, useRef } from "react"
   import { ScrollArea } from "@/components/ui/scroll-area"
   import { cn } from "@/lib/utils"
   import type { Message } from "@/lib/types"

   type MessageListProps = {
     messages: Message[]
   }

   export function MessageList({ messages }: MessageListProps) {
     const bottomRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null)

     useEffect(() => {
       bottomRef.current?.scrollIntoView({ behavior: "smooth" })
     }, [messages])

     if (messages.length === 0) {
       return (
         <div className="flex flex-1 items-center justify-center text-muted-foreground">
           Ask anything to start researching.
         </div>
       )
     }

     return (
       <ScrollArea className="flex-1 w-full">
         <div className="flex flex-col gap-4 p-4">
           {messages.map((msg) => (
             <div
               key={msg.id}
               className={cn(
                 "max-w-[80%] rounded-lg px-4 py-3 text-sm",
                 msg.role === "human"
                   ? "self-end bg-primary text-primary-foreground"
                   : "self-start bg-muted text-muted-foreground"
               )}
             >
               {msg.content}
             </div>
           ))}
           <div ref={bottomRef} />
         </div>
       </ScrollArea>
     )
   }

3. **Update the home page** to hold message state and wire both components together:
   tsx
   "use client"

   import { useState } from "react"
   import { ChatInput } from "@/components/chat-input"
   import { MessageList } from "@/components/message-list"
   import type { Message } from "@/lib/types"

   export default function HomePage() {
     const [messages, setMessages] = useState<Message[]>([])

     function handleSubmit(query: string) {
       const human: Message = { id: crypto.randomUUID(), role: "human", content: query }
       const ai: Message = { id: crypto.randomUUID(), role: "ai", content: "(placeholder AI response)" }
       setMessages((prev) => [...prev, human, ai])
     }

     return (
       <main className="flex flex-col h-screen max-w-3xl mx-auto p-4 gap-4">
         <MessageList messages={messages} />
         <ChatInput onSubmit={handleSubmit} />
       </main>
     )
   }

4. **Verify auto-scroll:** Add several messages until the list overflows and confirm it scrolls to the latest.
5. **Run `npm run build`** — fix any errors before closing.

## Context
The `useRef` + `scrollIntoView` pattern is React's way of interacting with the real DOM when declarative state isn't enough — analogous to obtaining a direct object reference in Java rather than going through an abstraction. The `useEffect` hook runs a side-effect (scrolling) after the component re-renders with new messages, similar to a `@PostConstruct` or an observer callback. Message state lives in the parent page and is passed down as props, following React's unidirectional data flow.

## References
- [React: useRef](https://react.dev/reference/react/useRef) — accessing DOM nodes directly
- [React: useEffect](https://react.dev/reference/react/useEffect) — running side effects after renders
- [shadcn/ui: ScrollArea](https://ui.shadcn.com/docs/components/scroll-area) — styled scrollable container component
- [shadcn/ui: Card](https://ui.shadcn.com/docs/components/card) — card layout primitives if you choose to use them for message bubbles
- [MDN: Element.scrollIntoView()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Element/scrollIntoView) — browser API used for auto-scrolling

## User Story
As a user, I want the chat interface to connect to the FastAPI backend and stream real AI responses token-by-token, so that I receive live research output instead of waiting for a complete response.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] The `@langchain/langgraph-sdk` package is installed in `/web`
- [ ] A `useResearch` custom hook exists at `web/src/hooks/use-research.ts` that wraps `useStream()`
- [ ] Submitting a query from `ChatInput` sends the request to the backend and streams the response
- [ ] Each streamed token appends to the in-progress AI message bubble in real time
- [ ] `ChatInput` is disabled (shows loading spinner) while a stream is in progress
- [ ] The streaming stops cleanly when the backend sends the final chunk
- [ ] Network errors display a user-visible error message rather than silently failing
- [ ] The FastAPI backend is running locally and the hook successfully connects to `http://localhost:8000`
- [ ] No TypeScript errors (`npm run build` is clean)

## Technical Tasks
1. **Install the LangGraph JS SDK:**
   bash
   cd web && npm install @langchain/langgraph-sdk

2. **Verify the FastAPI backend exposes an SSE endpoint.** The backend (from M2) should have a route like:

   POST /api/research/stream

   that accepts `{ "query": "..." }` and returns a Server-Sent Events stream. Start it with:
   bash
   uv run uvicorn src.api:app --reload --port 8000

3. **Create the custom hook** at `web/src/hooks/use-research.ts`:
   ts
   "use client"

   import { useState, useCallback } from "react"
   import type { Message } from "@/lib/types"

   const BACKEND_URL = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_BACKEND_URL ?? "http://localhost:8000"

   export function useResearch() {
     const [messages, setMessages] = useState<Message[]>([])
     const [isLoading, setIsLoading] = useState(false)
     const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null)

     const submit = useCallback(async (query: string) => {
       setIsLoading(true)
       setError(null)

       // Add human message immediately
       const humanMsg: Message = { id: crypto.randomUUID(), role: "human", content: query }
       // Create a placeholder AI message that will be updated as chunks arrive
       const aiMsgId = crypto.randomUUID()
       setMessages((prev) => [...prev, humanMsg, { id: aiMsgId, role: "ai", content: "" }])

       try {
         const response = await fetch(`${BACKEND_URL}/api/research/stream`, {
           method: "POST",
           headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
           body: JSON.stringify({ query }),
         })

         if (!response.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`)
         if (!response.body) throw new Error("No response body")

         const reader = response.body.getReader()
         const decoder = new TextDecoder()

         while (true) {
           const { done, value } = await reader.read()
           if (done) break
           const chunk = decoder.decode(value, { stream: true })
           // SSE lines start with "data: "
           for (const line of chunk.split("\n")) {
             if (line.startsWith("data: ")) {
               const token = line.slice(6)
               setMessages((prev) =>
                 prev.map((m) =>
                   m.id === aiMsgId ? { ...m, content: m.content + token } : m
                 )
               )
             }
           }
         }
       } catch (err) {
         setError(err instanceof Error ? err.message : "Unknown error")
       } finally {
         setIsLoading(false)
       }
     }, [])

     return { messages, isLoading, error, submit }
   }

4. **Update the home page** to use `useResearch()`:
   tsx
   "use client"

   import { useResearch } from "@/hooks/use-research"
   import { ChatInput } from "@/components/chat-input"
   import { MessageList } from "@/components/message-list"

   export default function HomePage() {
     const { messages, isLoading, error, submit } = useResearch()
     return (
       <main className="flex flex-col h-screen max-w-3xl mx-auto p-4 gap-4">
         {error && <p className="text-sm text-destructive text-center">{error}</p>}
         <MessageList messages={messages} />
         <ChatInput onSubmit={submit} isLoading={isLoading} />
       </main>
     )
   }

5. **Configure CORS on the FastAPI backend** so `localhost:3000` can call `localhost:8000`. In `src/api.py`:
   python
   from fastapi.middleware.cors import CORSMiddleware
   app.add_middleware(
       CORSMiddleware,
       allow_origins=["http://localhost:3000"],
       allow_methods=["*"],
       allow_headers=["*"],
   )

6. **Add environment variable support.** Create `web/.env.local`:

   NEXT_PUBLIC_BACKEND_URL=http://localhost:8000

   (This file is gitignored by default; create `web/.env.local.example` with the same content for documentation.)
7. **Test end-to-end:** Start the backend, start the frontend (`npm run dev`), submit a query, and watch tokens stream into the AI message bubble.

## Context
Server-Sent Events (SSE) is a browser-native protocol for server-to-client streaming over HTTP — the server pushes newline-delimited `data: <payload>\n\n` chunks. The `ReadableStream` API used here is the browser's standard way to consume streaming responses. In Java terms, this is similar to reading from an `InputStream` in a loop. The custom `useResearch` hook is idiomatic React: it encapsulates async logic and state so the page component stays clean — comparable to a Java Service class hiding business logic from a Controller.

## References
- [@langchain/langgraph-sdk: useStream() hook](https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraphjs/reference/classes/langgraph_sdk.Client.html) — official SDK reference
- [MDN: Server-Sent Events](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Server-sent_events/Using_server-sent_events) — how SSE protocol works
- [MDN: Fetch API / ReadableStream](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/ReadableStream) — streaming response body in the browser
- [React: useCallback](https://react.dev/reference/react/useCallback) — memoizing functions in custom hooks
- [FastAPI: CORS Middleware](https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/cors/) — enabling cross-origin requests
- [Next.js: Environment Variables](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/guides/environment-variables) — NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix for client-side env vars

## User Story
As a user, I want AI response messages to render Markdown formatting (headers, bold, bullet lists, code blocks) as they stream in token-by-token, so that structured research output is readable rather than displayed as raw text.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] `react-markdown` is installed and AI message bubbles render Markdown
- [ ] Markdown features work correctly: headers (`#`, `##`), bold (`**`), bullet lists (`-`), numbered lists, inline code, and fenced code blocks
- [ ] Streaming tokens append correctly without layout thrashing or full re-renders of the message list
- [ ] Code blocks are visually distinct (monospace font, background color)
- [ ] Human messages continue to render as plain text (no Markdown processing)
- [ ] No TypeScript errors (`npm run build` is clean)

## Technical Tasks
1. **Install `react-markdown`:**
   bash
   cd web && npm install react-markdown

2. **Update the AI message bubble** in `web/src/components/message-list.tsx` to use `ReactMarkdown`:
   tsx
   import ReactMarkdown from "react-markdown"

   // Inside the message map:
   {msg.role === "ai" ? (
     <ReactMarkdown
       components={{
         // Style code blocks
         code({ className, children }) {
           return (
             <code className={cn("bg-muted px-1 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono", className)}>
               {children}
             </code>
           )
         },
         pre({ children }) {
           return (
             <pre className="bg-muted p-3 rounded-md overflow-x-auto text-xs font-mono my-2">
               {children}
             </pre>
           )
         },
         // Style bullet lists
         ul({ children }) {
           return <ul className="list-disc list-inside my-2 space-y-1">{children}</ul>
         },
         ol({ children }) {
           return <ol className="list-decimal list-inside my-2 space-y-1">{children}</ol>
         },
         // Style headers
         h2({ children }) {
           return <h2 className="text-base font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">{children}</h2>
         },
         h3({ children }) {
           return <h3 className="text-sm font-semibold mt-2 mb-1">{children}</h3>
         },
       }}
     >
       {msg.content}
     </ReactMarkdown>
   ) : (
     <span>{msg.content}</span>
   )}

3. **Test with a mock Markdown response.** Temporarily hard-code a Markdown string as the AI response in `handleSubmit` to verify rendering before connecting to the real backend:
   ts
   const sampleMarkdown = `## Research Summary\n\n**Key finding:** LangGraph supports streaming.\n\n- Point one\n- Point two\n\n\`\`\`python\nprint("hello")\n\`\`\``

4. **Verify streaming behavior:** With the real backend connected (M5-6), confirm tokens accumulate correctly and Markdown renders progressively as partial Markdown is appended. Partial Markdown (e.g., `**bol` before `d**`) should not crash the component — `react-markdown` handles this gracefully.
5. **Run `npm run build`** and fix any TypeScript errors.

## Context
`react-markdown` is a React component that takes a Markdown string as its `children` prop and renders it as safe HTML. It re-renders on every state update (new token), which is fine because React's virtual DOM diffing ensures only changed parts of the DOM are updated — there is no full page repaint. This is analogous to data binding in Java UI frameworks: the model updates, the view reconciles automatically.

## References
- [react-markdown: README](https://github.com/remarkjs/react-markdown) — usage, props, and the `components` customization API
- [React: Rendering lists](https://react.dev/learn/rendering-lists) — understanding React's reconciliation (why streaming updates are efficient)
- [MDN: CSS font-family: monospace](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/font-family) — background on monospace fonts used in code blocks

## User Story
As a user, I want a sidebar that lists my past research sessions by title and date, so that I can revisit and review previous research reports.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] A `HistorySidebar` component exists at `web/src/components/history-sidebar.tsx`
- [ ] The sidebar lists past sessions with a title (truncated query) and relative timestamp (e.g., "2 hours ago")
- [ ] Clicking a session navigates to a URL like `/session/[id]` and renders that session's report
- [ ] A `src/app/session/[id]/page.tsx` dynamic route page exists and fetches session data from the backend
- [ ] The sidebar shows an empty state message when no history exists
- [ ] Session history persists across page refreshes (fetched from the backend `GET /api/sessions` endpoint)
- [ ] No TypeScript errors (`npm run build` is clean)

## Technical Tasks
1. **Create the dynamic route page** at `web/src/app/session/[id]/page.tsx`:
   tsx
   import { ReportView } from "@/components/report-view"
   import type { Report } from "@/lib/types"

   async function getSession(id: string): Promise<Report> {
     const res = await fetch(
       `${process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_BACKEND_URL}/api/sessions/${id}`,
       { cache: "no-store" }
     )
     if (!res.ok) throw new Error("Session not found")
     return res.json()
   }

   export default async function SessionPage({ params }: { params: { id: string } }) {
     const report = await getSession(params.id)
     return (
       <main className="p-8">
         <ReportView report={report} />
       </main>
     )
   }

2. **Create a session list type** in `web/src/lib/types.ts`:
   ts
   export type SessionSummary = {
     id: string
     query: string
     createdAt: string
   }

3. **Create `web/src/components/history-sidebar.tsx`:**
   tsx
   "use client"

   import Link from "next/link"
   import { ScrollArea } from "@/components/ui/scroll-area"
   import { cn } from "@/lib/utils"
   import type { SessionSummary } from "@/lib/types"

   type Props = {
     sessions: SessionSummary[]
     currentId?: string
   }

   function timeAgo(iso: string): string {
     const diff = Date.now() - new Date(iso).getTime()
     const mins = Math.floor(diff / 60000)
     if (mins < 60) return `${mins}m ago`
     const hours = Math.floor(mins / 60)
     if (hours < 24) return `${hours}h ago`
     return `${Math.floor(hours / 24)}d ago`
   }

   export function HistorySidebar({ sessions, currentId }: Props) {
     if (sessions.length === 0) {
       return <p className="p-4 text-xs text-muted-foreground">No past sessions yet.</p>
     }
     return (
       <ScrollArea className="h-full">
         <ul className="flex flex-col gap-1 p-2">
           {sessions.map((s) => (
             <li key={s.id}>
               <Link href={`/session/${s.id}`}
                 className={cn(
                   "block rounded-md px-3 py-2 text-sm hover:bg-muted transition-colors",
                   s.id === currentId && "bg-muted font-medium"
                 )}>
                 <p className="truncate">{s.query}</p>
                 <p className="text-xs text-muted-foreground">{timeAgo(s.createdAt)}</p>
               </Link>
             </li>
           ))}
         </ul>
       </ScrollArea>
     )
   }

4. **Create a root layout with sidebar** at `web/src/app/layout.tsx` — fetch the sessions list server-side and pass to `HistorySidebar`:
   tsx
   import { HistorySidebar } from "@/components/history-sidebar"

   async function getSessions() {
     try {
       const res = await fetch(`${process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_BACKEND_URL}/api/sessions`, { cache: "no-store" })
       return res.ok ? res.json() : []
     } catch { return [] }
   }

   export default async function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
     const sessions = await getSessions()
     return (
       <html lang="en">
         <body className="flex h-screen">
           <aside className="w-64 border-r shrink-0"><HistorySidebar sessions={sessions} /></aside>
           <div className="flex-1 overflow-auto">{children}</div>
         </body>
       </html>
     )
   }

5. **Ensure the FastAPI backend** has `GET /api/sessions` and `GET /api/sessions/{id}` endpoints that return session summaries and full session data respectively (this may require a backend task to persist completed sessions).
6. **Verify routing:** `npm run dev`, navigate to `/session/some-id`, confirm the page renders or shows a not-found error appropriately.

## Context
Next.js App Router uses **file-system routing**: a file at `src/app/session/[id]/page.tsx` automatically handles URLs matching `/session/*`, where `[id]` is a dynamic segment — similar to Spring MVC's `@PathVariable`. The `Link` component from Next.js is the idiomatic way to navigate between pages; it prefetches routes in the background for instant transitions, unlike a plain `<a>` tag which triggers a full page reload.

## References
- [Next.js: Dynamic Routes](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/building-your-application/routing/dynamic-routes) — `[id]` segment syntax and params
- [Next.js: Link component](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/api-reference/components/link) — client-side navigation
- [Next.js: Layouts](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/building-your-application/routing/layouts-and-templates) — shared layouts and nested routing
- [Next.js: Data Fetching in Server Components](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/building-your-application/data-fetching/fetching) — fetch() in async Server Components
